peiodic classifcation means putting the element with similar charcaterstics together in single row and column is knwon as periodic classification: the grouping and all these form is known as periodic classification:

** Mnadleve periodic table:
When elements are arranged in increasing atomic mass, elements with similar properties repeat at regular intervals. so it was based on atomic masses not on atomic no:

features:
| Feature                   | Description                                 |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| Basis of arrangement      | Atomic mass                                 |
| Total elements            | 63                                          |
| Periods (horizontal rows) | 7                                           |
| Groups (vertical columns) | 8 main groups (I to VIII)                   |
| Sub-groups                | Each group had **A & B** sub-groups         |
| Gaps                      | Left blank spaces for undiscovered elements |

** achivemnst of mandelve:
1) prediction of few element that they will exits in future and leave the blank space for them aka silicon : germanium, eka- boron= scandium:
2)corrected atomic masses: eg Berrylium:
3) elemet with similar property came in same group:

**Drawbacks:
| Point                | Explanation                                                          |
| -------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Based on atomic mass | Modern table uses atomic **number**, not mass                        |
| Position of isotopes | Isotopes not explained (same element, different masses)              |
| Hydrogen position    | Hydrogen didn‚Äôt fit clearly (Group 1 or 17?)                         |
| Anomalous pairs      | Some elements placed wrong due to atomic mass rule e.g., **Co & Ni** |

Example:
| Element | Atomic Mass | Position Issue |
| ------- | ----------- | -------------- |
| Co      | 58.9        | Came before Ni |
| Ni      | 59.0        | Came after Co  |

**Summary:
| Topic            | Key Point                             |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Periodic Law     | Atomic mass basis                     |
| Predictive Power | Very successful                       |
| Groups           | 8 (A & B)                             |
| Periods          | 7                                     |
| Major drawback   | Couldn't explain isotopes & anomalies |

Newlands law of octave:
When elements are arranged in increasing order of atomic mass, every eighth element has properties similar to the first, like musical octaves.
This means:
Element 1 and 8 are similar,
2 and 9 are similar, etc., just like Sa‚ÄìRe‚ÄìGa‚ÄìMa‚ÄìPa‚ÄìDha‚ÄìNi‚ÄìSa üé∂

**Achivements:
| Point                                                   | Benefit |
| ------------------------------------------------------- | ------- |
| ‚úî First to arrange elements in order of **atomic mass** |         |
| ‚úî Found periodicity in chemical properties              |         |
| ‚úî Basis for later periodic tables                       |         |

Limitation
| Problem                                                  | Description |
| -------------------------------------------------------- | ----------- |
| ‚ùå Worked only till Calcium (Ca)                          |             |
| ‚ùå After Ca, elements didn't follow 8th pattern           |             |
| ‚ùå Newlands tried to fit **two elements in one position** |             |
| ‚ùå Didn‚Äôt leave gaps for **new elements**                 |             |
| ‚ùå Did not work for **transition elements**               |             |


**Modern periodic table:
The physical and chemical properties of elements are periodic functions of their atomic numbers.
üìå Atomic number (Z) = Number of protons in an atom
(Mendeleev used atomic mass; modern uses atomic number)

** Classificatiom:
| Feature                   | Details                                    |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Total elements            | **118**                                    |
| Periods (horizontal rows) | **7**                                      |
| Groups (vertical columns) | **18**                                     |
| Blocks                    | **s, p, d, f**                             |
| Basis of arrangement      | **Atomic number + Electron configuration** |

** Periods:
| Period | Electrons Shell | No. of Elements | Nature            |
| ------ | --------------- | --------------- | ----------------- |
| 1st    | K               | 2               | Very short period |
| 2nd    | L               | 8               | Short period      |
| 3rd    | M               | 8               | Short period      |
| 4th    | N               | 18              | Long period       |
| 5th    | O               | 18              | Long period       |
| 6th    | P               | 32              | Very long period  |
| 7th    | Q               | 32 (Incomplete) | Very long period  |

**Groups:

| Group | Name                    |
| ----- | ----------------------- |
| 1     | Alkali Metals           |
| 2     | Alkaline Earth Metals   |
| 3‚Äì12  | Transition Elements     |
| 13    | Boron Family            |
| 14    | Carbon Family           |
| 15    | Nitrogen Family         |
| 16    | Oxygen/Chalcogen Family |
| 17    | Halogens                |
| 18    | Noble Gases             |


** Blocks of periodic table:
| Block   | Group Range     | Type                                              |
| ------- | --------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| s-block | 1‚Äì2             | Metals                                            |
| p-block | 13‚Äì18           | Metals + Non-metals + Metalloids                  |
| d-block | 3‚Äì12            | Transition metals                                 |
| f-block | Separate bottom | Inner transition metals (Lanthanides & Actinides) |

‚úÖ Metals, Non-metals, Metalloids

Metals: Left side (Na, K, Ca)

Non-metals: Right side (C, N, O, S, Cl)

Metalloids: B, Si, Ge, As, Sb, Te

** Periodic trends
| Property               | Across Period (‚Üí) | Down Group (‚Üì) |
| ---------------------- | ----------------- | -------------- |
| Atomic size            | ‚Üì decreases       | ‚Üë increases    |
| Ionization energy      | ‚Üë increases       | ‚Üì decreases    |
| Electronegativity      | ‚Üë increases       | ‚Üì decreases    |
| Metallic character     | ‚Üì decreases       | ‚Üë increases    |
| Non-metallic character | ‚Üë increases       | ‚Üì decreases    |

